359â†’/**
360â†’ * A helper to delay (debounce) execution of a task that is being requested often.
361â†’ *
362â†’ * Following the throttler, now imagine the mail man wants to optimize the number of
363â†’ * trips proactively. The trip itself can be long, so he decides not to make the trip
364â†’ * as soon as a letter is submitted. Instead he waits a while, in case more
365â†’ * letters are submitted. After said waiting period, if no letters were submitted, he
366â†’ * decides to make the trip. Imagine that N more letters were submitted after the first
367â†’ * one, all within a short period of time between each other. Even though N+1
368â†’ * submissions occurred, only 1 delivery was made.
369â†’ *
370â†’ * The delayer offers this behavior via the trigger() method, into which both the task
371â†’ * to be executed and the waiting period (delay) must be passed in as arguments. Following
372â†’ * the example:
373â†’ *
374â†’ * 		const delayer = new Delayer(WAITING_PERIOD);
375â†’ * 		const letters = [];
376â†’ *
377â†’ * 		function letterReceived(l) {
378â†’ * 			letters.push(l);
379â†’ * 			delayer.trigger(() => { return makeTheTrip(); });
380â†’ * 		}
